### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: 600<n><n>Input: Michael makes birdhouses to sell at craft shows. He charges $22 for each large birdhouse, $16 for each medium birdhouse, and $7 for each small birdhouse. This week, he sold 2 large birdhouses, 2 medium birdhouses, and 3 small birdhouses. How much money, in dollars, did he make this week?<n>Output: 97<n><n>Input: Nalani had two female dogs that were expecting and after a month gave birth to 10 puppies each. She then sold 3/4 of the puppies after they came of age, each at $200. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. Another box holds half the amount of the first box and 5 ounces less than the third box. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input:The sanctions against the school were a punishing blow, and they seemed to what the efforts the school had made to change? Choices:  A: ignore B: enforce C: authoritarian D: yell at E: avoid<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input: When you are studying how do you react when you can't understand something? Choices: 1. You continue to study 2. You ignore the difficulty to learn it anyway 3. You give up the study and do something you<n>Output: C<n><n>Input: If someone has a problem he or she should try to solve this by? Choices:  a. trying to solve it alone b. using common sense c. trying to solve it with friends d. being independent e. consulting books<n>Output: C<n>

Choices:  A: side B: main C: anterior D: current E: front<n>Output:		E<n><n>```<n>Solution:<n>The output is E.<n><n>The choices were: A, B, C, D, E. There is a word that is repeated four times. It<n>is current! It can't be B, because it is not repeated at all. It can't be D,<n>because it is not used at all. It can also be E or F because they are used the<n>same number of times. But B and D are both repeated four times. Only E is<n>repeated four times once. Therefore, the solution is E.<n><n>In the next post, I will show you that the logic puzzle questions are very<n>interesting and fun.

Don't forget to press Enter after your answer: ")<n><n>    for i in range(len(question)):<n>        if re.match(r'.*(\d{1,5})[\D]', question[i]):<n>            return re.search(r'.*(\(\d{1,10}\))', question[i]).group(0)<n>        elif re.match(r".*{n\d+}*", question[i]):        <n>            return re.findall(r'.*(\(n\d+\))', question[i])[0]<n>        <n>        else:    <n>            return ""<n><n>    ans = "None"<n>    if not ans:<n>        return ans<n>    else:<n>        return ans[-1]<n><n>print(get_answer())<n>

In that case, you will want to have the code debug. Here is how:<n><n>Create a new file in your python 3 IDE, call it test.py and paste in these lines:<n><n>```<n>def test_function():<n>    print('Testing 1, 2, 3')<n>    print('Test 4, 5, 6')<n>    print('test 1 2 3 + 2 6 1')<n>```<n><n>Paste this code in the file you just created and save it as test.py. Now, open another terminal and enter: python3 -m unittest discover to launch the unittest module. It will show you the output as seen below:<n>```<n>File "/usr/libexec/python3.4/unittest/__main__.py", line 433<n>self.fail(msg)<n>             ^<n>SyntaxError: invalid syntax<n><n><n>WARNING: Could not import test module:<n>File /usr/libexec/py34-unittest/__main__:1: in <module><n> <n>File <string>:1: in <module<n>```<n><n>This means that there was some sort of error. Now, how do you fix it?<n><n>Add a semicolon at the end of the line, inside of the curly brackets and then run it again. It

On a separate day, there are 40 students taking a test. How many students passed the class if 45 students passed the test?<n><n><n>First, count the total number of students who were not allowed to pass a single class(those who didn't take the test): <n><n>```<n><n>Total number of students taking a test in class = 50<n><n>```<n><n><n>This is the same number of students who did not take the test because they didn't pass. In fact, if anyone passes the first challenge, they will fail the second one.<n><n>We can then say that the number of students who cannot pass the test is:<n><n>```<n><n>50 - 45 = 5<n><n>```<n><n>Second, counting the number of students that were not allowed to pass their second semester exam. <n><n><n>```<n>5 - 4<n><n>4<n>```<n><n><n>Third, the number of students who passed. <n><n><n>As a result, everyone who passed either had an average of 60 percent above that grade, so the number of students who failed was five, and two students who passed their second round of testing, a total of seven.<n>

Choices:  a: house b: building c: tower d: skyscraper e: library<n>Output: : a: house<n>"<n>### Challenge:<n><n>Challenge: Given a number of candys and a difference between two persons, write a function that returns how many candys does the weaker person have.<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>Solution 1:<n><n>```python<n>def howManyCandys(numberOfCandy, candyDifference):<n>    numberOfCandy = int(numberOfCandy)<n>    candyDifference = int(candyDifference)<n>    result = 0<n>    firstPersonNumberOfCandy = numberOfCandy - candyDifference<n>    if(candyDifference > 0):<n>        result = firstPersonNumberOfCandys<n>    elif(firstPersonNumberOfCandies < 0):<n>        numberOfCandy = 66-(candyDifference) <n>    return result<n>    <n>```<n>Solution 2:<n>```python<n>def candys(candys, weaker):<n>    weaker = int(weaker)<n>    if ( candys < weaker):<n>        print (66 - weaker)<n>    elif:<n>        if ( candys > weaker):<n>            print(candys)<n>        elif (candys == weaker):<n>            candys<n>```<n><n><n><n>### Answer:<n>> The number of candys that weaker person has is:<n>- candyDifference = 8<n>- numberOfCandy =66. We need to subtract candyDifference from numberOfCandy because Tapanga has 1 more candy than Corey.<n>```<n> howManyCandys() : 66 - candyDifference.<n><n>Result = 29<n>```<n>    <n>

Like many immigrants at the time, Czechs and Slovaks went around to seek employment at farms to escape harsh times in their homeland and poverty. Many of them first came to America in the 1850s, although many stayed where there was work in Chicago and other cities. At that time, they were mostly lumberjacks, construction workers and railroad builders. Czech and Slovak families began to settle in the U.S. in the latter 1840s. In Cedar Rapids, Iowa, a small town settled mostly by Bohemians (Czechs), the first school was built and opened in January of 1852. The school was built by the people themselves. They raised funds and built a small wooden schoolhouse. The community had a few families and a few hundred people in total. It had one hotel and three stores.<n><n>-----------------------------------------------------------<n><n>### Instructions:<n><n>1. Well be playing a bit of the game. Choices:  A: demonstration B: conference C: building D: garage E: mouth<n>Output:		C<n><n>####### Solution<n><n>Use the first method. That is, you take a "brute force" approach to the problem and just try each statement until you find the correct output.<n><n>In these problems you could write a list which contains the given input data and some extra values which could be calculated beforehand, like `num_candies [52,36]` or `longest_word [8]`.<n>After creating the list, you could simply go over this by executing a for -loop and adding the correct answers to the variable `answers [10,15,12,24,160,1,3,33,97,500]` by a simple if condition.<n><n>```python<n>num_candies = [52, 36]<n>longest_word = [8]<n>answers = [10, 15, 12, 24, 160, 1, 3, 33, 97, 500]<n><n>for i in num_candies:<n>    if i[1] == 8:<n>        if i[0] < 8:<n>            temp = i[0]<n>        else:<n>            temp = 8<n>    if temp[-1] == 2:<n>        temp = temp[0]<n>    if temp[2] == 8:  # 10<n>        temp = temp[:-1]<n>    elif temp[-1] == '0' and temp[-2] == 'x' and temp <= 800 and 800!= temp:<n>         if len([a for a in temp if a.isnumeric() and not a == 0]) == 4:  #160<n>                           <n><n>        if temp[0] == 'x':<n>            if temp[1] == 'x': # 500<n>                temp = temp[:-3]<n>            else:<n>                temp = temp[0:1]<n>    if temp in longest_word: # 33<n>        temp = temp.strip('x')<n>    print(temp)<n>```<n><n>###### Second Example<n><n>```python<n>input = 'My friend and I ate the pants of a clown.'<n>num = 6<n>output

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. But in our case, the element are sorted in descending order<n>        # so we need to reverse the array<n>        if len(nums) > 1:<n>

The first number is always positive.<n><n>For example:<n>+1 10<n>+5 9<n>-4  6<n>-2  3<n>*7  9<n>* 7<n>There are 6 numbers in this sequence `1 +9 -4 -2 -3 +9 +7`. To get the final result, simply perform the operations `1 * 7 -4 -2 -2 * 6`.<n>The final output is 0.<n><n>Your solution will consist of a single-line string, representing the final result of the computation.<n><n>In the above example, `1 +9 - 4 -2 - 3 * 9 - 2 * 6 = 0`.<n>

He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: 600<n><n>Input: Michael makes birdhouses to sell at craft shows. He charges $22 for each large birdhouse, $16 for each medium birdhouse, and $7 for each small birdhouse. This week, he sold 2 large birdhouses, 2 medium birdhouses, and 3 small birdhouses. How much money, in dollars, did he make this week?<n>Output: 97<n><n>Input: Nalani had two female dogs that were expecting and after a month gave birth to 10 puppies each. She then sold 3/4 of the puppies after they came of age, each at $200. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. Another box holds half the amount of the first box and 5 ounces less than the third box. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input:When would you be able to see your reflection in a piece of wood? Choices:  A: burned B: polished C: carved D: composted E: nailed<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input:Which one is not a common symptom of anemia? Choices:  fatigue, paleness, shortness of breath, weakness<n>Output: D<n><n>Input:What is the probability of drawing three red cards from a pack of cards? Choices:  $0.125,  $0.16,  $0.24,  $0.32<n>Output:  C<n><n>Input:How many times is a word in the dictionary that contains an "e" and "f" in it? Choices:   once,  twice,  thrice,  none<n>Output: D<n>\end{code}<n><n>I would like to have the correct answer in the Output, and i want to remove the brackets and numbers that surround the output, which i could do myself using sed command. I'd like to automate the whole process. Please help<n><n>Answer: Firstly, why do you have `\r` in your file?<n><n>You can get the correct answers with this awk command :<n><n>\begin{code}<n>awk -F\" '{getline;print $4} END{close("-")>0}' myinput.txt<n>\end{code.}<n><n>Then you can get rid of brackets and white space with this awk command : `tr -d \"`<n><n>And finally you can add some indents :<n><n>\begin<n>{code}<n>awk '<n>BEGIN{<n>    FS="[,"<n>}<n>{<n>    split ($4,a,"[+-*/]")<n>    print "/*", a[1], "*/\n",  $4"/61792599"<n>}<n>END{<n>    if ($0=="END"){<n>        close("-")>0<n>        print "//"$4"/61760863"<n>    }<n>}' file<n>\end{code}.<n><n>[How to execute awk from python?](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/21410003/how-to-execute-awk-from-python)

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. Thus, the correct answer must be C.<n><n>### Part 2:<n>Input: On Tuesday, 1/10/07, how many seconds will pass before 1/10 of 24 hours have passed?<n>Answer: 240 seconds / 24h = 10 seconds.<n><n>## Instruction: You are given a list of cities and their population in number of citizens. You are to answer the city which is the most populated. However, the list of the city and citizens population can be rearranged. Find the most populated city.<n>  Input:<n><n>Input: Los Angeles: 616,587   <n>Detroit: 598,470   <n>Chicago: 636,048   <n>Los Angeles: 623,780   <n>Chicago : 500,998   <n>Detroit : 554,942<n>Output: Los Angeles, 675,570<n>---<n># Challenge:<n>### Part 1:<n>Input: If 2 years ago you had -35 dogs, and two years previous to that you had 222 dogs, how many dogs did you have 4 years ago.<n>Output: 194<n><n>### Part2:<n>Input: Tara is given 2 cards of the same value and 1 card of different value. How many ways can Tara pick 3 cards such that they form 3 different combinations of the same value?<n>Output: 8<n><n>### Answer Explanation:<n><n>Case 1: The first card has the first two values and the second card has the last two values. We will look at combinations (a, b, c) and (b, c, a) where a, b, and c are all unique, so there are 3! ways to do this.<n><n>Case 2: The first card has one of the first two values and second card has the last value (or vice versa). In this case, there are 2! for the first card, 2! for the second card, and 2! ways to arrange both cards, resulting in a total of 4
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. What are the three numbers?<n><n>If 9 = 5\+ 2 = 7 \+ 1,<n><n>Then we can find that 9 = 1 * 2 * 3 = 2 * 2 * 2 = 3 * 3 * 1.<n><n>So, there are an infinite amount of ways this expression can be expanded, but we are only looking for three solutions.<n><n>2 \+ 5 + 1<n><n>4 * 2, 3 * 3, and 1 * 1. 4 + 2 = 6<n><n>12 \+ 5 \+ 1<n><n>13 * 3 and 3 * 2. 13+5=38+1= 39 = 1 *. 39<n><n>18 + 5 + 1

Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: 600<n><n>Input: Michael makes birdhouses to sell at craft shows. He charges $22 for each large birdhouse, $16 for each medium birdhouse, and $7 for each small birdhouse. This week, he sold 2 large birdhouses, 2 medium birdhouses, and 3 small birdhouses. How much money, in dollars, did he make this week?<n>Output: 97<n><n>Input: Nalani had two female dogs that were expecting and after a month gave birth to 10 puppies each. She then sold 3/4 of the puppies after they came of age, each at $200. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. Another box holds half the amount of the first box and 5 ounces less than the third box. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input:When he was a small child he called the giraffe mascot a cow, it was a fond memory of the now defunct what? Choices:  A: toy store B: story book C: great outdoors D: countryside E: wildlife refuge<n>Output:		A<n>

Choices:  A: happen to people B: hurt people C: happen anytime D: happen often E: happen anywhere<n>Output:		C<n>https://raw.githubusercontent.com/dev-ninja-saransh/leetcode-coding-competition/master/Leet%20Code%20Coding%20Competition%20-%20Round%203%2C%20Day%206/LCC_Round3_Day6_1/README.md<n><n># Q1.<n><n>https://leetcode.com/explore/card/top-interview-questions-easy/39/strings/264/<n><n>## Method:<n><n>```python<n># O(n)<n>def reverseString(self, s: str) -> str:<n>        ans=""<n>        for i in range(len(s)-1,-1,-1):<n>              ans=ans+s[i]<n>    <n>        return ans<n>```<n>## Result: Accepted | Runtime: 0.220s | Memory Usage: 6.5MB<n>******************************************************************************************************<n># Q2.<n><n>https://www.lintcode.com/problem/minimum-total-distance/description<n><n>```python<n>class Solution:<n>    def minTotalDistance(self, nums1: List[int], nums2: List[int]) -> int:<n>        if not nums2:<n>            return nums1<n>        return abs(nums1[0]-nums2[0])+ self.minTotalDistance(nums1[1:],nums2[1:])<n><n>```<n><n>## Result: Acceptede | Runtime: 0s | Memory Usagiage: 3.8MB<n>*************************************************************<n># Q3.<n><n>https://practice.geeksforgeeks.org/problems/minimum-distance-to-find-11/1<n><n>## Method: :<n><n>```python<n><n>def minDistanceFrom1To1(list):<n>       ans =1000000<n>       for i in range(0,len(list)-1):<n>             if list[i]==1:<n>                  ans = len(list)-i<n>          return ans<n>    ans =minDistanceFrom1To1([1,0,2])<n>

In the following examples we have two basic data structures:<n><n>* Integer<n>* Array<n><n>Example:<n>```python<n># A simple python script<n>a = 1<n>b = 3<n>c = [2,1,4,3]<n>print(a, b, c)<n>```<n>Example output:<n>```<n>1 3 [2, 1, 4, 3]<n>```<n><n>### Functions: What is a function?<n><n>Whenever you run a function, you pass it arguments. Arguments could be numbers like 23, strings like "hi", or variables like a = 21. The function will then perform some sort of operation on the arguments.<n><n>### Recursion<n>```python<n>def my_recursive_fnc(arg):<n>   if true:<n>      return True<n>   else:<n>      return False<n>```<n>### Control Flow: <n>- For loops<n>- While loops<n>- If/else statements<n>- If/else if statements<n>- Ternary statements<n><n>### Data Collection Techniques<n><n>- Input: Asks for a user input, like a number, string or something else<n>- Console.WriteLine: prints some string to the screen, use if for debugging<n>- Console.Read();: Asks the user for an input<n>---<n><n>### Data Structures Explanation:<n>Arrays:<n>- An array is a collection of similar values stored at contiguous memory locations. The values of an array are stored in contiguous memory locations starting at address and continuing up to address + size. <n>- Arrays are often used to represent a list of items or to represent a matrix.<n>```<n>int[] someIntArray = new int[10];<n><n>```<n><n>---<n><n>Boolean:<n>A Boolean literal is a value that evaluates to either TRUE or FALSE. It is similar in use to the C language.<n><n>Boolean variables do not need to be declared, but they do need to have a data type:<n><n>```<n>int var1 = 3;<n>byte var2 =

How many trips will it make to transport 600 passengers?<n>Output:<n><n>### Challenge:The following are two different problems that involve figuring out the answer by comparing the number of people to the number of seats on airplanes.<n><n>Input1: The economy class of a Boeing 747 Jumbo Jet of the Philippine Airlines from Manila to Rome is full with 10 people. How many people are on the plane?<n>Output1: 224<n><n>Input2: The first-class section of the same plane for the Rome to Manila leg is full with 30 people. How many seats are in the first-class section?<n>Output2: 44 Business class, and 304 economy class <n><n>Answer: The first question asks you to divide the number of people by the number seats in the economy class (200 people/8 people) to get the number of planes.<n>The second question asks you to divide 30 people by 2 (first-class seats) and 4 (business-class seats) to get the answer.<n>

Choices:  A: birthday party B: child's hand C: grocery store D: sky E: up in the<n>Output:		birthday party<n><n>"""<n><n><n># This function adds up all the values of the array<n># input: an array<n># output: the sum of the array<n>def arraySum(array):<n>    sum = 0<n>    for number in array:<n>        sum += number<n>    return sum<n><n><n># This is the primary function of the program<n>print(arraySum([8, 2, 12, -10, 4]))<n>

The first one is first-person view of what someone would see if they were standing in front of the object. The second is a top-down view of what someone would be seeing while flying over an object. The third is a side-view that looks at an object from a side-angle. The last one is 3D.<n>-What would an object be made out of if it were made into a 3D model and how would that work from what's just been said? <n>-An object made from 3D model could be made out of a plastic like material or metallic substance like aluminum or iron, it would then have to be shaped into the right shape to look like the object in question.<n>-Let's say we used an object such as a glass for example and we wanted 3D printing so what do we do?<n>-We could use a 3D printer to create a working 3D glass that you could drink from.<n>-Imagine you needed a 3D glass like in what was just mentioned. If you needed to make a glass would it be real glass like on a real object?<n>-Yes, real glass would be used to make a 3D object.<n>

The amone among first and second persons is " + amone+", the amount that is left with the 3rd, 4th and 5th person is " + rest;<n>        if(rest<=2){<n>            System.out.println(("The no. of ways of distribution is "+3*3*3));<n>        }<n>        else if(rest==3){<n>            System.err.println("This can't be done");<n>        }<n>       <n>    }<n>}<n>```<n><n><n>### Output:<n><n>``` java<n>There are two persons.

How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. Choices:  A: unfeeling B: negligence C: antipathy D: indifferent E: rapport<n>Output:		C<n><n>Input:Betty ate a sandwich and a cup of coffee at a restaurant for \$5.01, but she didn't have enough to pay for her food. The next week, she ate a burger, fries, and a drink for \$6.55, but she didn' t have quite enough dollars left for that either. What did she eat at the first restaurant?<n> Output: sandwich<n><n>Input:A man goes for training and in a 80 minutes he takes an exercise for 10 mins walk and then 16 minutes rest and after that 16 minutes running and in end 8 mins resting in the same way he do for 1 times. He does this 3 rounds with in 24 hours of a day,which one takes 2 hrs 30 mins.<n>Output:<n><n>**Explanation: **<n><n>In first round the man takes 20 minutes for walk,10 minutes for running,4 minutes for resting and 4 minutes for running.So on for 5 rounds,<n>2*0 minutes+0+10+16+0+16+8+4 minutes=80+36+16+76+32=260 minutes.<n>Now 2hrs=120 minutes and 1hr=60 minutes,60+240=300 minutes.<n>Therefore,he takes 300/260 minutes=1.15 minutes per round.<n>We multiply it with 3 rounds,1.15X3=3.45 minutes/round.

Choices:  A: question B: dispute C: deny D: contradict E: refuse<n>Output:		C: Deny<n><n><n>###### Coderbyte Solutions<n><n>```python<n>numcandies = (0, -8, 8, 0, -1, 1, 2, -5, 4)<n><n>if numcandies[0] > numcandies[1]:<n>	print(numcandies[0])<n>elif numcandies[2] > numcandys[0]:<n>	print(24)<n>elif numcandys[2] > num candys[1]:<n>	#the second is bigger than the first<n>	print(28)<n>else: <n>	#the first is bigger than the second<n>	print(29)<n><n>minutecost = (1, 2, 5, 25, 15, 15)<n><n>cents = 0<n>localcost = 0<n>internationalcost = 0<n><n>for m in minutecost:<n>	localcost = m<n>	internationalcost = m<n><n>if localcost == internaionalcost:<n>	#this only happens if same local and international costs<n>	cents = minutecost[0] * 2<n>	print(cents)<n>elif localcost > internaionalcost:	<n>	localcost *= 2<n>	internationalcost *= 2	<n>cents = minutecost[-1] * 2<n>print(cents)	<n><n>worked hours = (0, -10, -22)<n>totalhours = 0<n>hoursperday = 0<n><n>hoursperday *= -1<n>totalhours += workeds hours[0]<n>hoursperday += 4<n>totalhours += worked hours[1]<n>hoursperdays += 4<n>totalperhours += worked hours[-1]<n> <n>print(totalhours)<n><n>bookcount = (0, 10, 0, 0, -5)<n>numnotsold = bookcount[0]<n> <n>bookcount[0] -= bookcount[1]<n>numnotsold += bookcount[0] + numnotsold<n><n>print(numnotsold)<n><n>prices = (0, 0, [-10])<n>money = 0<n>bought bird

Eugene earned $20 more than Michael. Ravi earned $6 more than Tina. Ali earned $30 in all. If Eugene earned twice as much as Ravi and Ravi earned $3 more than Ali, how much did each earn?<n><n># **Solution**<n>It is important to note that there are two unknowns within the statement for the solution of the problem.<n><n>In such cases, one must use the elimination of options to find the solution.<n><n>For this case, Tina's wages must be 15, because she earned the least.<n><n>This is true despite the fact that Ravi is second-highest, because if we subtract Ravi's 20 from the total, the answer will come 70, which is not valid.<n><n>Tapanga has made the most money, which is 45.<n><n>Since Tina is next on the list, her earnings are 29, and Eugene has 22 and Miya has 20 since the sums are not balanced.<n><n>Total: <n><n># **Answer (100%)**<n><n>45, 29, 22, 20, 15<n><n># **Question4**<n><n>There are 3 boxes that contain cereal, one box of cereal holds 14 ounce of cereal, another box holds half the amount as

How much money in dollars do you pay?<n><n>Input/output<n>- In the problem above, the number of the books in the first pile is 247 and the number of the books with less than or equal to 35 are 76 which is rounded to 75 due to rounding down.<n><n>## Task<n><n>Use the Python language to solve the following task.<n>- Implement the logic to find the number of the books you can buy less than or equal to the number 35.<n>- The output can be either the number 76 or 75.<n><n>## Output<n><n>You have to output the number of the books that you can buy less than 35.

Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. How much money, in dollars, did he make this week?<n>Output: 97<n><n>Input: Nalani had two female dogs that were expecting and after a month gave birth to 10 puppies each. She then sold 3/4 of the puppies after they came of age, each at $200. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. Another box holds half the amount of the first box and 5 ounces less than the third box. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input:The woman experienced great joy, but despite that this was a what? Choices:  A: drop to zero B: increase C: cool down D: dropping quickly E: heat up<n>Output:		E<n><n>### Output: What does each of the following have in common?<n><n>Choice: Dogs, cats, frogs, fish, birds <n><n>### Output is: All are living things <n><n>**Explanation:**<n><n>All the animals mentioned above are living things, except frogs. <n>### Explanation:<n><n>"**All cats are dogs.**"<n><n>From the statement, we can infer that if the proposition "All dogs are cats" is _true,_ then the _conclusion_ "Some cats are dogs" is also _true,_ or _valid._  However, we cannot make any such conclusion from the negative sentence " **No cats are dogs. **"  **<n>### Explanations:<n><n>- All bachelors are unmarried<n>- No married men are bachelors<n><n>* * *<n><n>### Question: **Output**<n><n>### Outputs: <n><n>**All girls are cute.**<n><n>### Reason: <n><n>### <n><n>### Turtles can breathe on land and in water.<n><n>**Explanations:**<n><n>Turtles can survive on both land and water. This means that turtles can survive in a world with no water, just as they can survive in a water-less world. Conversely, we can see that if turtles cannot survive in one world or another, then they cannot survive in both worlds simultaneously. But this is clearly false, since we have already established that turtles are both on land and in water at the same time! <n><n><n>### The statement implies that if the turtles can breat<n><n>The statement implies that if the "turtles can breat" then the worlds must be of the same kind, in which case, the "worlds can exist without water" or "worlds should have water." <n><n><n>```python<n>print_explanation(turtles_and_worlds) # prints 2 explanations<n>```<n><n><n><n><n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. Tapanga has 38 more candies than his friend<n>2. Therefore in ratio x is 38 more than y. 38 : 1 = 38y/1 = 8y<n>3. Therefore total number of candies is 66 + 8y = 74Y. However Tapanga has 27 more candies than Coreay so. 8y = 27. 3y = 27/2. Y = 27/4 = 6. Therefore Corey Has 27 - 6 = 21 candies<n>4. In total, Freddie spent $10. A local call cost $0.05 and an international call cost $0.25. The rate for a local call is 65% of the rate for an international call. Set up an equation. 65% times how much is spent on international calls is $5. 100 percent times how much is spent local calls is $0.25 times $45 = $11.25. Therefore the answer is 65% or 0.65 times $11.24 = 0.65 x $11.2 = 7.28. The total amount spent on the phone call is therefore: 0.25

Therefore, Tapanga has a total of 28 candies and Corey has 29 candies, making them equal to each other. <n><n>#### Problem4<n>Input:<n>If Freddie is in the same city. Then, the call is 0.05*45=2.25. So, the total cost is 2.25+7.75=9.95<n><n>#### Problem5<n>Input:<n>If the work for the same hours for every day, the 5.5+5.5+5=15 hours, then his work for 7 days (157=105)<n><n>#### Problem 6<n>Input: if the day and week not change, then Ali will have no sale on other 3 days (100-600=400).<n><n>#### Problem 7<n>Input:<n>If he sells large birdhouse for $ 22.00. So he made $44<n><n><n>#### Problem 8<n>Input:<n>Nalani sold (0.75*15+0.75*7)=27.50 for first dog. <n><n>So, for second dog, Nalani made $50<n><n>#### Problem 9<n>Input:<n>We can get Boris's book.<n><n>32+24*44=68+102= 170<n><n>We can get Cameron's book.<n>30*33=99<n><n>We can get Borris and Cameron's book together.<n>170+99=270 <n><n>#### Problem10<n>Input:<n><n>0.75+0.5-5= 10 Ounce<n>We can get 2 boxes. <n>So the third box will have 14*3=42 Ounce<n>

Answer choices: A. 1 B. 3 C. 8 D. 12 E. 16<n><n>Output: E<n>```<n><n>This program takes input of multiple choice questions and output the correct answers. it takes the input from a `.txt` file and creates a `dictionary`. Then the program splits the lines of the input file into three parts, the question part, The answer part, and the answer key part. Then the program uses the dictionary to store the lines where the question part matches the name of the file. The problem with this is that the dictionary will hold the question as key and the whole line (`"""`), which is the line number (key) that matches the question name and the whole answer line as value. Then the program tries to iterate over the keys in this dictionary and iterate over the lines in the text file based on the key (number of the line that matches that part). it calls `get_question_key_index` to find the key index for that line of the input file. This function calculates the first index (`key_start_index`) of the key(part of the input text file) using the [`find`](https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#str.find)builtin method for strings. This function also finds the length of the key using [`len`](https://docs.openstack.org/lumina-docs/latest/reference/api/python/lumina.html?highlight=len#lumina.len). After getting the first index `key_start_index` and the length of the key `len_key` we get the `index` of the key in the dictionary using the [`bisect`](https://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy/reference/generated/numpy.bisect.html?highlight=bisect) builtin function. Then using this index

"E" is not a possible answer, because the question does not ask about "speeding the plane up". 4. The correct answer is "crash". The correct answer is "A". <n><n>#### Explanation<n><n>The cabin in an aircraft is a place where passengers get inside an aircraft to have access to the cockpit. As such, the answer can only be "A", for the reason "crash".  <n><n>#### Example Usage<n>  * 'The cabin in an airplane is used to carry passengers.'<n><n>

If Tapanga is younger than Corey, find the difference. <n><n>```<n>Input: Tapaga = 8 and Corey = 10 <n>Output: Tapanga is two years younger than Corey (10 - 8 = 2). <n><n>Input: Tapeanga = 10 and Corey = 8 <n>Output: Tapeanga is 2 years younger than Corey. <n>```<n><n>--- <n><n>**Explanation**: <n><n>In this case, you can directly use an array as they both do not contain many numbers.<n><n>We need a function to receive two numbers as input and we need to find whether the first number is greater than the second one or vice versa.<n><n>The easiest way is to use "if" and "return".<n><n>Here is the code.<n><n>```java <n>package com.java.javaexpo; <n> <n>public class Code {    <n> <n> // Function to find the difference between two numbers. <n> <n> public static int findDifference(int a, int b) { <n> <n> 	// If a is greater than b, return 1. <n> <n>  if (a > b) return 1; <n> <n>   // If a is less than b, return -1. <n> 	if (a < b) return -1; <n> 	<n> return 0; <n> <n> } <n> <n> // Driver method. <n><n>	public static void main(String[] args) { <n>	<n>	 int a = 8; <n>	 int b = 10; <n>	 <n>	 System.out.println(findDifference(a, b)); <n>	 <n> } <n>} <n>```<n><n>Here we define a function called findDifference(). We will pass two integers in this function.<n><n>Then, we check whether a is greater than b or vise-versa. If it is so, we return 1, -1 for small and large numbers respectively

So we can rewrite this equation as: 8 = C - Tapanga_candies. Solving gives C = 33. Tappana has candies = 29.<n><n>**Example**2.<n><n>The number of minutes Freddy spent talking on New Year's eve is equal to 45 minutes + 31 - 5 * 90. The number of international minutes is equal to 31 minutes and the number of local minutes is 90. So we can rewrite the equation as: (x + 31) - 5 *90 = 10. Solving yields the solution: x - 450 = 10 which is: x = 450 + 10 = 460.<n><n>**Example 3.**<n><n>The number of hours is equal to 4 * 8 + 5.5 * 2 - 8 * 5.5. To solve this we can equate the number of hours Freddy works each day to n and rearrange it in the terms of n. So we can write 4 * 8 = n * 2 which is: 8 = 2 * n. Then n - 4 = 5.5 which is: n = 6.65. The correct solution is 6.<n><n>**Example4.**<n><n>The problem statement gives the total number of books Ali had before the sale i.e. 800. It then subtracts the amount of books sold and tells us how many books were not sold. However, the answer given is 600. But, this answer is wrong as 600 books were never in Ali's possession. So, clearly there is something missing in the question statement.<n><n>The books were 4 days old. Ali had the books in the week starting from Monday and continuing to the next four days. On the other hand

Choices:  A: shopping mall B: hospitals C: populated area D: school E: military base<n>Output:		 D<n><n><n><n><n>### Instruction:Answer the questions below<n><n>    - What are some of the limitations in writing a language interpreter which uses a tokenizer and parser?<n>A parser is really only a tool. It accepts tokens and generates a data structure.<n>    There's nothing about a parser that's specific to programming languages.<n>    That's why it's used by a variety of applications such as regular expression editors, lexical analyzers for compilers, pattern matchers,<n>    etc.  Parsers are used for a variety of things because parsing is what is needed in general.<n>    You have got to parse in order to produce some output.<n>    The language interpreter is just one example of an application of a parser, and a very specialized application in that.<n>    It's not what is usually done by a parser.<n>    There aren't any special limitations other than the fact that the input lexer, you have to produce the tokens in the right order to be a good lexer.<n>But that's not really a limitation as the language itself is what it is, you just have to follow it and that shouldn't be too difficult.<n>    - Given the following program segment, can you interpret the code?<n><n>    int main() {<n>        printf("hello, world!"); //0-based indexing<n>    }<n>-----------------<n>    It would be interpreted as hello, world!<n>-----------------<n>    - Does a recursive descent parser allow for better performance compared to a LL(k) parser? <n>    Recursion is not as fast as LL(k) which is one of the major disadvantages of recursive descent. It has to call a subroutine to<n>    process what has been matched. Each time you call a subroutine, you pay the overhead of the call.<n>    But that's not usually the major problem with recursive descent. It's got its main drawback and that's the fact that recursion<n>    itself is very difficult to implement efficiently in most programming languages.<n>    What is a recursive function? It returns the value, it returns what it returns. Does that make sense?<n>    It's very difficult to really understand recursion fully even for experienced programmers.<n>    It' is often the case that recursion makes programs faster but it's also the case that recursion generally results is longer<n>    programs and code.<n>

Ten<n>Output: 2. 10<n><n>### Instruction: Answer the following true or false and short answer questions.<n><n>Question 1: A variable is a name that represents an item.<n><n>Answer:  A variable is a name chosen to stand for a certain piece of information called an item.  It is used to store or retrieve a piece of information.  A variable can store a number, which can be useful when doing arithmetic. In computer programming, a variable is a named entity in a program that holds a value. Variables are used to represent all kinds of data.<n><n>Short Answer Question 1: What is a Function in programming?<n><n>Answer: The function is a program that is written to perform one task using a given set of inputs. Functions are programs, similar to your favorite toy program, which take in inputs and produce an output.<n><n>True or False Question 2: A for loop is used to process all of the elements in an array.<n><n>Answer: True, For loop provides a means for executing exactly the same set of statements iteratively for every element in a collection such as an array, a list, or a string.<n><n>True or false Question 3: All variables are also objects?<n><n>Answer: False, A Variable is the value that can be assigned to. An object is a tangible entity. Variables are the storage places of values, and as such is used all the time.<n><n>True or FALSE Question 4: All variables hold values, true or

You can use arrays if you have a more complex problem and you think you will need to sort, reorder, or iterate through a lot of values within the problem. This is a common way to store values we want to retrieve later in the problem and can significantly reduce the amount of times we have to process the values. Arrays, when used properly, can speed up a programs performance or its efficiency.<n><n># Instructions:<n><n>Instructions: In Problems 1 through 8, write a JavaScript program that defines multiple arrays.
